'john-strauss-associates','','','2012-12-04 05:37:59','2012-12-04 05:37:59','',87,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/john-strauss-associates.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(92,1,'2012-12-04 05:37:59','2012-12-04 05:37:59','','Time Lord','','inherit','open','open','','time-lord','','','2012-12-04 05:37:59','2012-12-04 05:37:59','',87,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/time-lord.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(93,1,'2012-12-04 05:42:41','2012-12-04 05:42:41','','John Strauss Associates','','private','closed','closed','','john-strauss-associates','','','2013-03-07 19:47:10','2013-03-07 19:47:10','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=93',23,'portfolio-piece','',0),(94,1,'2012-12-04 05:43:22','2012-12-04 05:43:22','','Time Lord: An Argon Augmented Reality Experience','','private','closed','closed','','time-lord-an-argon-augmented-reality-experience','','','2014-02-03 21:27:08','2014-02-03 21:27:08','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=94',24,'portfolio-piece','',0),(95,1,'2012-12-04 05:44:38','2012-12-04 05:44:38','','Night Rydazz','','publish','closed','closed','','night-rydazz','','','2019-08-21 23:36:09','2019-08-21 23:36:09','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=95',22,'portfolio-piece','',0),(96,1,'2012-12-04 05:44:23','2012-12-04 05:44:23','','Night Rydazz','','inherit','open','open','','night-rydazz','','','2012-12-04 05:44:23','2012-12-04 05:44:23','',95,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/night-rydazz.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(97,1,'2012-12-04 06:06:58','2012-12-04 06:06:58','[applet code=\"P1.class\" file=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/fermat-point-calculation.jar\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\"]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo calculate the shortest path between the three points, click and drag the vertices of the triangle (A, B, and C).\r\n\r\nSource code: <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.pde\">P1</a>\r\nCreated by <i>Russell Strauss</i>.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nCS3451 - Fall 2010 taught by Jarek Rossignac\r\n\r\nProblem:\r\nThree points can be placed anywhere in space. Find the path of least distance that connects all three points. The program must be dynamic and controlled by the user.\r\n\r\nSolution:\r\nIn a triangle, the point that connects all three vertices with the least amount of distance is known as the Fermat Point {citation <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat_point\">here</a>}.\r\nCalculating the Fermat Point consists of the following steps:\r\n1. Determine whether the triangle has any angle greater than (or equal to) 120 degrees. If so, then the Fermat Point is the vertex of the angle that is greater than 120 degrees.\r\n2. If no angles are greater than 120 degrees, then form three equilateral triangles created by each edge of the original triangle created by A, B, and C.\r\n3. Form lines connecting the outer vertex of each equilateral triangle to the opposite vertex of the original triangle (A, B, or C).\r\n4. Where these lines intersect is the Fermat Point. The paths connecting the three points with the least amount of distance are the paths from each vertex to the Fermat Point, represented above by the lightest shade of blue.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Solution in pseudocode:</b>\r\n<i>\r\n</i>[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.txt\" /]\r\n\r\nNote: This is only the highly simplified pseudocode. To see the exact code with in-depth comments, see the source code <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.pde\">here</a>.\r\nZip file <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.zip\">here</a>.','Fermat Point Calculation','','publish','closed','closed','','geometric-shortest-distance-between-three-points','','','2012-12-19 06:39:07','2012-12-19 06:39:07','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=97',25,'portfolio-piece','',0),(98,1,'2012-12-04 06:06:26','2012-12-04 06:06:26','','P1','','inherit','open','open','','p1','','','2012-12-04 06:06:26','2012-12-04 06:06:26','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/P1.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(99,1,'2012-12-04 06:06:28','2012-12-04 06:06:28','','P2','','inherit','open','open','','p2','','','2012-12-04 06:06:28','2012-12-04 06:06:28','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/P2.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(100,1,'2012-12-04 06:06:28','2012-12-04 06:06:28','','P3B','','inherit','open','open','','p3b','','','2012-12-04 06:06:28','2012-12-04 06:06:28','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/P3B.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(101,1,'2012-12-04 06:06:29','2012-12-04 06:06:29','','P3f','','inherit','open','open','','p3f','','','2012-12-04 06:06:29','2012-12-04 06:06:29','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/P3f.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(102,1,'2012-12-04 06:08:34','2012-12-04 06:08:34','&lt;div id=\"P2b_container\"&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;!-- This version plays nicer with older browsers,\r\nbut requires JavaScript to be enabled.\r\nhttp://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/technotes/guides/jweb/deployment_advice.html\r\nhttp://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/deployment/deploymentInDepth/ --&gt;\r\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"\r\nsrc=\"http://www.java.com/js/deployJava.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\r\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;\r\n/* &lt;![CDATA[ */\r\n\r\nvar attributes = {\r\ncode: \'P2b.class\',\r\narchive: \'P2b.jar,jl1.0.jar,jsminim.jar,minim-spi.jar,minim.jar,mp3spi1.9.4.jar,tritonus_aos.jar,tritonus_share.jar,core.jar\',\r\nwidth: 800,\r\nheight: 600,\r\n};\r\nvar parameters = {\r\nimage: \'loading.gif\',\r\ncenterimage: \'true\',\r\n};\r\nvar version = \'1.5\';\r\ndeployJava.runApplet(attributes, parameters, version);\r\n\r\n/* ]]&gt; */\r\n&lt;/script&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;noscript&gt; &lt;div&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if !IE]&gt; --&gt;\r\n&lt;object classid=\"java:P2b.class\"\r\ntype=\"application/x-java-applet\"\r\narchive=\"P2b.jar,jl1.0.jar,jsminim.jar,minim-spi.jar,minim.jar,mp3spi1.9.4.jar,tritonus_aos.jar,tritonus_share.jar,core.jar\"\r\nwidth=\"800\" height=\"600\"\r\nstandby=\"Loading Processing software...\" &gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"archive\" value=\"P2b.jar,jl1.0.jar,jsminim.jar,minim-spi.jar,minim.jar,mp3spi1.9.4.jar,tritonus_aos.jar,tritonus_share.jar,core.jar\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"mayscript\" value=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"scriptable\" value=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"image\" value=\"loading.gif\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"boxmessage\" value=\"Loading Processing software...\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"boxbgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;!--&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;!-- For more instructions on deployment,\r\nor to update the CAB file listed here, see:\r\nhttp://java.sun.com/javase/6/webnotes/family-clsid.html\r\nhttp://java.sun.com/javase/6/webnotes/install/jre/autodownload.html --&gt;\r\n&lt;object classid=\"clsid:8AD9C840-044E-11D1-B3E9-00805F499D93\"\r\ncodebase=\"http://java.sun.com/update/1.6.0/jinstall-6u20-windows-i586.cab\"\r\nwidth=\"800\" height=\"600\"\r\nstandby=\"Loading Processing software...\"  &gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"code\" value=\"P2b\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"archive\" value=\"P2b.jar,jl1.0.jar,jsminim.jar,minim-spi.jar,minim.jar,mp3spi1.9.4.jar,tritonus_aos.jar,tritonus_share.jar,core.jar\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"mayscript\" value=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"scriptable\" value=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;param name=\"image\" value=\"loading.gif\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"boxmessage\" value=\"Loading Processing software...\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;param name=\"boxbgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n&lt;strong&gt;\r\nThis browser does not have a Java Plug-in.\r\n&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"http://www.java.com/getjava\" title=\"Download Java Plug-in\"&gt;\r\nGet the latest Java Plug-in here.\r\n&lt;/a&gt;\r\n&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/object&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;!--[if !IE]&gt; --&gt;\r\n&lt;/object&gt;\r\n&lt;!--&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/noscript&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\nDownload the application.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nClick and drag the circle to move it. If you click outside of the circle, it will react based on the distance from the click to the circle.\r\n\r\nThis is not specifically meant to be a game, but rather a dynamic physics simulation. The focus was not gameplay elements, but accurately reflecting physics in real time with user input.\r\n\r\nSource code: <a href=\"P2.pde\">P2</a> <a href=\"Flocking.pde\">Flocking</a> <a href=\"Missile.pde\">Missile</a> <a href=\"Prediction.pde\">Prediction</a> <a href=\"Spring.pde\">Spring</a> <a href=\"pv.pde\">pv</a>\r\nCreated by <i>Russell Strauss</i>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"left\" width=\"1090 px\" />\r\n\r\nCS3451 - Fall 2010 taught by Jarek Rossignac\r\n\r\n<b>Problem:</b>\r\nCreate an applet that the user can interact with. Have a target in the center that is controlled by the user with two projectiles flying towards the target. They must reach the target after exactly two seconds, alternating from left and right. The target must have inertia and the projectiles must predict the location of the target two seconds ahead of time. Detect and count collisions.\r\n\r\n<b>Simulation in pseudocode:</b>\r\n<blockquote><b>function inertia():</b>\r\n<blockquote>// This function uses equations for springs to create a delay between the time the mouse moves and when the ball moves.\r\n\r\nforce = -k * (tempypos - rest_posy); // f=-ky\r\naccel = force / mass; // Set the acceleration, f=ma == a=f/m\r\nvely = damp * (vely + accel); // Set the velocity\r\ntempypos = tempypos + vely; // Updated position\r\nforce = -k * (tempxpos - rest_posx); // f=-ky\r\naccel = force / mass; // Set the acceleration, f=ma == a=f/m\r\nvelx = damp * (velx + accel); // Set the velocity\r\ntempxpos = tempxpos + velx; // Updated position\r\n\r\n// Set values for the spring attributes:\r\nint size = (int)C.r;\r\nfloat damp = .8;\r\nfloat mass = 3;\r\nfloat springConstant = .1;\r\ndisplayTarget();</blockquote>\r\n<b>function aim(pt origin, pt target):</b>\r\n<blockquote>// This function aims the projectile towards the target, initializing it and calculating what initial velocity is required to reach the target in 2 seconds.\r\nVx = (target.x)/2.;\r\nVy = (target.y-screenHeight-2.*(Gravity.y))/2.;\r\nV0 = V(Vx,Vy);\r\nreturn V0;</blockquote>\r\n<b>function missile(pt origin, pt target):</b>\r\n<blockquote>// This function draws the missile and updates its velocity. It uses the Taylor series expansion of the physics equation of position to calculate the missile\'s velocity under constant acceleration, gravity.\r\n\r\nvel.x = futurePt.x/2; // Calculate x velocity.\r\nM.x = M.x + (vel.x)*(1./30); // Updates the x position of the missile vel.y = vel.y +(1./30)*(G.y); // Calculates the necessary y velocity to reach the target at exactly 2 seconds.\r\ndetectCollision(missile, target);</blockquote>\r\n<b>function detectCollision(pt missile, cir target):</b>\r\n<blockquote>// This function detects the collision between a given point and the target circle object.\r\nfloat xDistance = C.x - P.x;\r\nfloat yDistance = C.y - P.y;\r\nif (sqrt(sq(xDistance) + sq(yDistance)) &lt; C.r/2 ) {\r\nreturn true;\r\n}\r\nelse return false;</blockquote>\r\n<b>function prediction():</b>\r\n<blockquote>// This function tries to predict where the target will be in 2 seconds.\r\nmousePoint = P(mouseX, mouseY);\r\n// Creates an array with the position for the mouse trail.\r\nfor (int i=0; i&lt;10; i++) lastTrail[i] = mouseTrail[i];\r\nfor (int i=0; i&lt;9; i++) mouseTrail[i] = lastTrail[i+1]; // Shifts the index of the mouse positions each frame.\r\nmouseTrail[9] = mousePt; // Updates the new mouse position.\r\n// Creates ten points like this out of the last ten mouse positions.\r\npt p1 = P(mouseTrail[0].x, mouseTrail[0].y);\r\n...\r\npt p10 = P(mouseTrail[9].x, mouseTrail[9].y);\r\n// Averages the mouse positions\r\nfor (int i=0; i&lt;10; i++) {\r\navg.x += mouseTrail[i].x;\r\navg.y += mouseTrail[i].y;\r\n}\r\n\r\navg.x /= 10;\r\navg.y /= 10;\r\n// Creates a vector from the average of the mouse positions to the current mouse positions.\r\npredict = V(avg, mousePt);\r\nfuturePt = avg;\r\n// Translates a point past the predict vector (three times the length of that vector) to anticipate\r\n//where the ball is likely traveling.\r\nif (mousePressed) futurePt = T(futurePt, 2, predict);\r\nelse futurePt = P(target.x, target.y);\r\n// Resets the average.\r\navg = P(0,0);</blockquote>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nNote: This is only the highly simplified pseudocode. To see the exact code with in-depth comments, see the source code <a href=\"P2.pde\">here</a>.\r\nZip file <a href=\"P2.zip\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n<b>Extra credit:</b>\r\nI included sound effects in collision detection.\r\n\r\nI had the velocity of the missiles calculate dynamically to make the projectiles more unpredictable while in the air. This one way in which I made it more like a game.\r\n\r\n<b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Citations:</span></b>\r\nI used code from the Processing web site in a class called Springs to simulate the spring motion of the ball:\r\n<a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/topics/springs.html\">http://processing.org/learning/topics/springs.html</a>\r\n\r\nI used another class called Flocking that has no relevance with the assignment, but created a cool background effect:\r\n<a href=\"http://processing.org/learning/topics/flocking.html\">http://processing.org/learning/topics/flocking.html</a>\r\n\r\nI used an audio library named Minim to play sounds and music:\r\n<a href=\"http://code.compartmental.net/tools/minim/\">http://code.compartmental.net/tools/minim/</a>','Physics, projectiles, inertia, and movement prediction','','publish','closed','closed','','physics-projectiles-inertia-and-movement-prediction','','','2013-05-24 21:24:24','2013-05-24 21:24:24','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=102',26,'portfolio-piece','',0),(103,1,'2012-12-04 06:11:35','2012-12-04 06:11:35','[applet code=\"P3.class\" file=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/polygon-subdivision.jar\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\"]','Smoothing polygon & subdivision','','publish','closed','closed','','smoothing-polygon-subdivision','','','2013-05-24 21:41:12','2013-05-24 21:41:12','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=103',27,'portfolio-piece','',0),(104,1,'2012-12-04 06:12:27','2012-12-04 06:12:27','[applet code=\"P1.class\" file=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/fermat-point-calculation.jar\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\"]','3D rendering, rotation matrices, realistic center of gravity','','publish','closed','closed','','3d-rendering-rotation-matrices-realistic-center-of-gravity','','','2013-05-24 21:42:14','2013-05-24 21:42:14','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=104',28,'portfolio-piece','',0),(472,1,'2012-12-14 07:24:42','2012-12-14 07:24:42','','Game Development','','publish','closed','closed','','game-development','','','2019-08-22 00:07:07','2019-08-22 00:07:07','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/?post_type=portfolio-category&#038;p=472',12,'portfolio-category','',0),(105,1,'2012-12-06 01:48:16','2012-12-06 01:48:16','Our challenge for this application was to create our own paint program from scratch. The catch was that we were not allowed to use any sort of traditional painting tools. Pen, brush, line, box, were all out of the question. I decided to create a program in which the user can draw different nature scenes. His tools are elements of M