]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nTo calculate the shortest path between the three points, click and drag the vertices of the triangle (A, B, and C).\n\nSource code: <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.pde\">P1</a>\nCreated by <i>Russell Strauss</i>.\n\n<hr />\n\nCS3451 - Fall 2010 taught by Jarek Rossignac\n\nProblem:\nThree points can be placed anywhere in space. Find the path of least distance that connects all three points. The program must be dynamic and controlled by the user.\n\nSolution:\nIn a triangle, the point that connects all three vertices with the least amount of distance is known as the Fermat Point {citation <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat_point\">here</a>}.\nCalculating the Fermat Point consists of the following steps:\n1. Determine whether the triangle has any angle greater than (or equal to) 120 degrees. If so, then the Fermat Point is the vertex of the angle that is greater than 120 degrees.\n2. If no angles are greater than 120 degrees, then form three equilateral triangles created by each edge of the original triangle created by A, B, and C.\n3. Form lines connecting the outer vertex of each equilateral triangle to the opposite vertex of the original triangle (A, B, or C).\n4. Where these lines intersect is the Fermat Point. The paths connecting the three points with the least amount of distance are the paths from each vertex to the Fermat Point, represented above by the lightest shade of blue.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Solution in pseudocode:</b>\n<i>\n</i>[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.txt\" /]\n\nNote: This is only the highly simplified pseudocode. To see the exact code with in-depth comments, see the source code <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.pde\">here</a>.\nZip file <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/fermat/fermat.zip\">here</a>.','Fermat Point Calculation','','inherit','open','open','','97-autosave','','','2013-02-06 00:44:36','2013-02-06 00:44:36','',97,'http://jrstrauss.net/portfolio-new/97-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(513,1,'2013-01-29 03:51:55','2013-01-29 03:51:55','','LU decomposition error','','inherit','open','open','','luchart','','','2013-01-29 03:51:55','2013-01-29 03:51:55','',510,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/LUchart.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(511,1,'2013-01-30 03:47:00','2013-01-30 03:47:00','<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LU_decomposition\">LU Decomposition</a> is one of the most common methods of matrix decomposition. It results in one lower triangular matrix, L, and one upper triangular matrix, U. LU decomposition has a much simpler process than other methods of matrix decomposition, but cannot be calculated with as much accuracy as other methods, which is especially important when writing computer programs such as this one that can extend the iterations well beyond what can be done by a human.\n\nTo begin the decomposition, we first create the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_matrix\">Hilbert matrix</a>, which is the matrix that we will decompose in this problem, but the process can be performed with any desired matrix. The user is prompted to enter a dimension, and the program generates the Hilbert matrix (and each successive step in the process) based upon that dimension.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu1.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe decimal format is used to display the matrices in the terminal in a readable form, neatly organized. The next step is to calculate our vector b, given in the problem statement, which is simply a vector equal to the number of dimensions, n, with 1 in each element: {1, 1,..., 1}.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu2.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThroughout the calculation of the decomposition, we will need to use the identity matrix at various points, so we calculate it and store it into an array named I.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu3.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAfter creating the Hilbert matrix, identity matrix, and vector b, we can now start to calculate L and U. The matrix U consists of our original Hilbert matrix, row-reduced into an upper-triangular <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row_echelon_form\">row echelon form</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu4.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNext, we want to find the L matrix. At this point, finding L is very similar to finding U, except now we will add another for loop to the method. L starts out as the first column of our original Hilbert matrix. Next we need an identity matrix to work with, so we create it with two for loops and create a temporary matrix, tempL, and set it to the identity. Next, we use the tempL by dividing the elements in the Hilbert matrix (locally called “Matrix”) and multiply it by our variable L matrix to find the end product L matrix.\n\nIn other words, to find L, we want to find the inverse of the Hilbert matrix--what matrix when multiplied by the original matrix will equal the identity matrix. Performing the same row-reducing operations that we used to find U on the identity matrix will give us the lower triangular matrix L.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu5.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAs you can see, when evaluating our error, our LU algorithm is generally accurate, maxing out at 4.108e-14 at n=19, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Lb=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in UX=y to solve for X. Note: the larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) occurs as a result of using Python to solve for Hx-b, which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, the overall LU decomposition was successful and accurate.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/LUchart.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-513\" alt=\"LU decomposition error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/LUchart.png\" width=\"714\" height=\"485\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAnd when all put together:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu6.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;','LU Decomposition','','inherit','open','open','','510-autosave','','','2013-01-30 03:47:00','2013-01-30 03:47:00','',510,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/510-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(504,1,'2012-12-19 06:36:10','2012-12-19 06:36:10','','fermat','','inherit','open','open','','fermat','','','2012-12-19 06:36:10','2012-12-19 06:36:10','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/fermat.zip',0,'attachment','application/zip',0),(501,1,'2012-12-16 10:29:15','2012-12-16 10:29:15','','fermat-point-calculation','','inherit','open','open','','fermat-point-calculation','','','2012-12-16 10:29:15','2012-12-16 10:29:15','',97,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/fermat-point-calculation.jar',0,'attachment','application/java-archive',0),(502,1,'2012-12-16 10:30:47','2012-12-16 10:30:47','','projectile-simulation','','inherit','open','open','','projectile-simulation','','','2012-12-16 10:30:47','2012-12-16 10:30:47','',0,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/projectile-simulation.jar',0,'attachment','application/java-archive',0),(503,1,'2012-12-16 10:31:46','2012-12-16 10:31:46','','polygon-subdivision','','inherit','open','open','','polygon-subdivision','','','2012-12-16 10:31:46','2012-12-16 10:31:46','',0,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/polygon-subdivision.jar',0,'attachment','application/java-archive',0),(514,1,'2013-01-29 04:58:28','2013-01-29 04:58:28','<p>The first step in calculating our <a title=\"Householder transformation\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Householder_transformation\">Householder reflection</a> matrices is to find our a<sub>n</sub> (also notated a<sub>i</sub>) vector, which is calculated by vector X - ||c-e1||: the vector X is the first column of the Hilbert matrix, and c is the norm of vector X. We use the same method in calculating the Hilbert matrix and the vector b as used prior in LU decomposition.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders1.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>The next step is to find H(a<sub>1</sub>) which is found with the given equation:</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"add-border center\" alt=\"householder-equation-1\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-equation-1.jpg\" />\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders2.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>This will not only find H(a<sub>1</sub>), but also each subsequent H(a<sub>n</sub>) within the for loop, until we reach H(a<sub>n-1</sub>). After finding H(a<sub>n</sub>), we find H<sub>n</sub> but multiplying H<sub>n</sub> times A<sub>n-1</sub> which the first time through the loop is the Hilbert matrix.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders3.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>After going through the loop, the program will find H<sub>n</sub>, set our starting matrix, HCopy, to that H<sub>n</sub>, and then perform the loop over again, until we have found Q and R. At the end of each loop H<sub>n-1</sub> is multiplied by H<sub>n</sub> and stored into Q. And next, we found the max norm of QR-H:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders4.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>which uses the method we created for finding the max norm of a matrix:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/infinite-norm.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\"><img alt=\"householder-error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<p>As you can see, when evaluating our error, our Householder algorithm is generally very accurate, maxing out at 3.379e-15 at n=19, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Q<sup>t</sup>b=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in RX=y to solve for X. The larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) is because we used Python to solve for Hx-b which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, our QR Householder factorization was successful and accurate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the entire piece, unbroken:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders5.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>will output the following:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders-output.txt\" /]','QR Decomposition via Householder Reflections','','publish','closed','closed','','householder-reflection-decomposition','','','2018-04-24 20:24:44','2018-04-24 20:24:44','',0,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=514',0,'portfolio-piece','',0),(856,1,'2018-05-14 18:20:11','2018-05-14 18:20:11','<section class=\"contact left\">\r\n	<h2>Contact</h2>\r\n		\r\n		<div>\r\n			<div class=\"left\">\r\n				<ul class=\"plus\">\r\n					<li>Name</li>\r\n				</ul>\r\n			</div>\r\n			<div class=\"right\">\r\n				Russell Strauss\r\n			</div>\r\n			<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n		</div>\r\n		\r\n		<div>\r\n			<div class=\"left\">\r\n				<ul class=\"plus\">\r\n					<li>Phone</li>\r\n				</ul>\r\n			</div>\r\n			<div class=\"right\">\r\n				678.549.2874\r\n			</div>\r\n			<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\r\n		</div>\r\n		\r\n		<div>\r\