norm of QR-H:</p>\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders4.txt\" /]\n\n<p>which uses the method we created for finding the max norm of a matrix:</p>\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/infinite-norm.txt\" /]\n\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\"><img alt=\"householder-error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\" /></a>\n\n<p>As you can see, when evaluating our error, our Householder algorithm is generally very accurate, maxing out at 3.379e-15 at n=19, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Q<sup>t</sup>b=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in RX=y to solve for X. The larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) is because we used Python to solve for Hx-b which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, our QR Householder factorization was successful and accurate.</p>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAnd the entire piece, unbroken:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders5.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nwill output the following:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders-output.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;','QR Decomposition via Householder Reflections','','inherit','open','open','','514-autosave-v1','','','2018-04-24 20:23:45','2018-04-24 20:23:45','',514,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/514-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(516,1,'2013-01-29 05:18:27','2013-01-29 05:18:27','<p>Simply put, <a title=\"Givens rotations\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Givens_rotation\">Givens rotations</a> is a method of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_decomposition\">matrix decomposition</a>. Just as with polynomials in Algebra, a matrix can be factored into two separate matrices and used to solve a system of equations. There are many different methods of matrix decomposition, using Given rotations being one of them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following code will decompose the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_matrix\">Hilbert matrix </a>of any dimension with very high accuracy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To start out, we calculate the Hilbert matrix as explained in the previous problems. Again we created the identity matrix, and set both our Q and G<sub>n</sub> to the identity to begin with.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens1.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>Our first step is to calculate our rotation matrices to be used in multiplying and finding each G<sub>n</sub>. The cosine and sine squares move up and left in the matrix as we cancel out each element in the column. So for example, when we try to cancel out the bottom left element of the Hilbert matrix will start in the bottom right corner and as we move upward through the Hilbert matrix columns, the cosine and sine square in the rotation matrix will move up one row and left one column as we proceed. The rest of the elements are filled with the identity. It follows the form:</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"add-border center margin-bottom-small\" alt=\"rotation-matrix\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/rotation-matrix.jpg\" />\r\n\r\n<p>The values of cosine and sine are calculated with:</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"add-border center margin-bottom-small\" alt=\"sin-cos\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/sin-cos.jpg\" />\r\n\r\n<p>where b is the element in the Hilbert matrix that we are trying to cancel out, and a is the element above it. So to do this, I first calculated a and b:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens2.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>The i for loop begins the process and goes through the rows of the Hilbert matrix while the j loop goes through the columns, moving from bottom to top. The first time through the loop, A<sub>n</sub> equals our Hilbert matrix, the next time through, it will equal G<sub>1</sub>*Hilbert, or A<sub>1</sub>, and so forth. Now that we have found the values for our sinX and cosX variables, we will put them into their corrosponding places into the G<sub>n</sub> matrix.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens3.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>Next, we multiply G<sub>n</sub> with A<sub>n</sub> to find our A<sub>n+1</sub> and print our each matrix to make sure it is being calculated correctly. Then we multiply G<sub>n</sub>*Q. At the end of the process, this will represent Q = G<sub>n</sub>…G<sub>3</sub>G<sub>2</sub>G<sub>1</sub>.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens4.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>After doing this, we turn G<sub>n</sub> back into the identity and loop back through the process. Since A<sub>n</sub> has changed, it will redo the process with the new A<sub>n </sub>each time through the i loop.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens5.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>Now the only step left is to calculate the max norm of the error. The same method is used as in the previous problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Givens error:</p>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/givens-error.jpg\"><img class=\"add-border center margin-bottom-small\" alt=\"givens-error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/givens-error.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<p>As you can see, when evaluating our error, our Givens algorithm is generally very accurate, maxing out at 1.4641e-15 at n=17, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Q<sup>t</sup>b=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in RX=y to solve for X. The larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) is because we used Python to solve for Hx-b which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, our QR Givens rotation factorization was successful and accurate. The Givens method is overall much more stable than the other 2 methods, LU and Householders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The code in its entirety:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens-whole.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>And its output:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/givens/givens-output.txt\" /]','QR Decomposition via Givens Rotations','','publish','closed','closed','','qr-decomposition-via-givens-rotations','','','2018-04-24 20:31:38','2018-04-24 20:31:38','',0,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=516',0,'portfolio-piece','',0),(517,1,'2013-01-29 06:08:29','2013-01-29 06:08:29','<p>Each method of decomposition uses various basic fundamental matrix operations, as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Printing out matrices in a way that can be easily read and accurately displayed in the terminal:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To be able to view the results of our matrix operations and display the contents of the matrices, we must be able to print matrices in a form that is easily readable:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/print2d.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>We must also be able to do the same with 3D matrices (or arrays of matrices):</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/print3d.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>In order to calculated the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose\">transpose</a> of a matrix:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/transpose.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>Matrix subtraction:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/subtract.txt\