sp;</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n					\r\n</div>','Resume','','inherit','open','open','','77-revision-v1','','','2015-11-04 18:29:28','2015-11-04 18:29:28','',77,'http://portfolio.dev/77-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(699,1,'2015-11-04 21:33:05','2015-11-04 21:33:05','<p>In April of 2015, I left my home in Atlanta with two of my friends to drive up to Springer Mountain in north Georgia. We planned a 4-day backpacking trip from the peak of Springer, the southern terminus of the famous Appalachian Trail, to Neels Gap, 32 miles northeast. While Winston and Ryan, the two friends that had joined me for the weekend and Winston\'s dog, Orion, planned only to travel to Neels Gap before returning home to Atlanta, I had committed to something very different. I had spent the last year planning the logistics and mentally preparing to hike the entire length of the Appalachian Trail from start to finish within a single calendar year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can look anywhere for information on thru-hiking (hiking the length of a trail in a single trip) and find all sorts of statistics that will discourage you from attempting a thru-hike of the AT: \"Only 1 in 5 people who set out to thru-hike make it to the end of the trail\"; \"The elevation change in thru-hiking the AT is equivalent to climbing up and down Mount Everest 16 times\"; \"Many hikers give up within the first week and many others 1-2 months into the trip when the monotony of hiking for 8+ hours a day becomes no longer enjoyable\"; \"The Appalachian Trail is the wettest long distance hiking trail in the U.S.\"; and plenty of other anecdotes from hikers discussing the hardships of long distance hiking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But one of the most crucial facts that must not be forgotten is that despite all of the hardships that come with the nature of long distance hiking, many wonderful benefits accompany the lifestyle of a backpacker as well&mdash;a life without traffic, bills to pay, the bureaucratic frustrations of civilized life; a life without appointments or schedules to follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, though there are no schedules to follow, there is one schedule that relentlessly demands progress: walk. And that \"walk\" is certainly almost nothing like what you might casually visualize as a constant but leisurely stroll forward. It is a walk through mud pits, over boulders, up and down constant changes in elevation. It is waking up and moving as quickly as you can with over 30 pounds on your back until it\'s time to sleep. It is having to walk all day in the rain when you already got sick of being wet days ago. It is waking up and putting on your rain-soaked clothes in the cold, mountain air so that you will have dry clothes to sleep in. It is a walk full of tumbles and falls up and down huge slanted slabs of slippery, wet rock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But when you\'re not falling, when you\'re not walking in the rain, when you\'re not uncomfortable, hungry, or exhausted from carrying everything you need to live on your back, the sun shines brightly upon your face. You\'re soaked in sweat, but you\'re in charge of nothing but your own well-being. You have an infinite amount of freedom...as long as you never stop walking north. You physically struggle during the day, but find comfort in the incredible luxury of an instant packet of ramen noodles in the evening. So I wasn\'t going home until I had hiked the entire Appalachian Trail. I wasn\'t worried about the statistics. I had what I needed, and all I had to do was keep moving.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I walked from Georgia to Maine. I started in April and finished in October. I owned only what was light enough to carry on my back day after day across mountaintops for 2,200 miles. Even in these conditions, I often carried more than I <em>really</em> needed. The lifestyle of a backpacker is simple and serene. It is also rigorous and full of hardship.  If you ever get the opportunity to live with only what you can carry on your back, <em>I suggest you take it.</em>