.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(760,1,'2015-11-06 20:42:37','2015-11-06 20:42:37','','DCIM104GOPRO','','inherit','open','open','','dcim104gopro-16','','','2015-11-06 20:42:37','2015-11-06 20:42:37','',0,'http://portfolio.dev/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/60.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(761,1,'2015-11-06 20:42:42','2015-11-06 20:42:42','','DCIM100GOPRO','','inherit','open','open','','dcim100gopro-10','','','2015-11-06 20:42:42','2015-11-06 20:42:42','',0,'http://portfolio.dev/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(763,1,'2018-06-13 18:27:30','2018-06-13 18:27:30','<p>In April of 2015, I left my home in Atlanta with two of my friends to drive up to Springer Mountain in north Georgia. We planned a 4-day backpacking trip from the peak of Springer, the southern terminus of the famous Appalachian Trail, to Neels Gap, 32 miles northeast. While Winston and Ryan, the two friends that had joined me for the weekend and Winston\'s dog, Orion, planned only to travel to Neels Gap before returning home to Atlanta, I had committed to something very different. I had spent the last year planning the logistics and mentally preparing to hike the entire length of the Appalachian Trail from start to finish within a single calendar year.</p>\n\n<p>You can look anywhere for information on thru-hiking (hiking the length of a trail in a single trip) and find all sorts of statistics that will discourage you from attempting a thru-hike of the AT: \"Only 1 in 5 people who set out to thru-hike make it to the end of the trail\"; \"The elevation change in thru-hiking the AT is equivalent to climbing up and down Mount Everest 16 times\"; \"Many hikers give up within the first week and many others 1-2 months into the trip when the monotony of hiking for 8+ hours a day becomes no longer enjoyable\"; \"The Appalachian Trail is the wettest long distance hiking trail in the U.S.\"; and plenty of other anecdotes from hikers discussing the hardships of long distance hiking.</p>\n\n<p>But one of the most crucial facts that must not be forgotten is that despite all of the hardships that come with the nature of long distance hiking, many wonderful benefits accompany the lifestyle of a backpacker as well&mdash;a life without traffic, bills to pay, the bureaucratic frustrations of civilized life; a life without appointments or schedules to follow.</p>\n\n<p>Of course, though there are no schedules to follow, there is one schedule that relentlessly demands progress: walk. And that \"walk\" is certainly almost nothing like what you might casually visualize as a constant but leisurely stroll forward. It is a walk through mud pits, over boulders, up and down constant changes in elevation. It is waking up and moving as quickly as you can with over 30 pounds on your back until it\'s time to sleep. It is having to walk all day in the rain when you already got sick of being wet days ago. It is waking up and putting on your rain-soaked clothes in the cold mountain air so you will have dry clothes to sleep in. It is a walk full of tumbles and falls up and down huge slanted slabs of slippery, wet rock.</p>\n\n<p>But when you\'re not falling, when you\'re not walking in the rain, when you\'re not uncomfortable, hungry, or exhausted from carrying everything you need to live on your back, the sun shines brightly upon your face. You\'re soaked in sweat, but you\'re in charge of nothing but your own well-being. You have an infinite amount of freedom...as long as you never stop walking north. You physically struggle during the day, but find comfort in the incredible luxury of an instant packet of ramen noodles in the evening. So I wasn\'t going home until I had hiked the entire Appalachian Trail. I wasn\'t worried about the statistics. I had what I needed, and all I had to do was keep moving.</p>\n\n<p>I walked from Georgia to Maine. I started in April and finished in October. I owned only what was light enough to carry on my back day after day across mountaintops for 2,200 miles. Even in these conditions, I often carried more than I really needed. The lifestyle of a backpacker is simple and serene. It is also rigorous and full of hardship.  If you ever get the opportunity to live with only what you can carry on your back, <em>I suggest you take it.</em></p>\n\n\n\n\n<div class=\"photo-thumbnails\" id=\"AT-photos\">\n\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Day 1: The Southern Terminus. Only 2189 miles ahead.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/01-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/01-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Winston joins me on the short but foggy hike to the Southern Terminus, April 2nd, 2015.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/02-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/02-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The first month on the trail was nothing but rain.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/03-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/03-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A view from within the Nantahala River in North Carolina\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/04-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/04-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Newfound Gap, in the middle of the famously beautiful Great Smoky Mountains\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/05-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/05-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Climbing out onto Charlie\'s Bunion, Great Smoky Mountains\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/06-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/06-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A beautiful sunny day in Virginia\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/07-1024x631.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/07-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"There\'s absolutely nothing to complain about in this weather.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/08-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/08-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"My camp site on Hump Mountain, a huge yet completely bald grassy mountain with views in 360 degrees.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/09-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/09-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"McAfee\'s Knob overlooking Catawba Valley, Virginia. A very popular day-hike location with one of the most incredible views on the AT.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/10-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/10-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A happy day walking through the fields of Virginia\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/11-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/11-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"An unexpectedly pleasant field of wild black-eyed susans thrive in the corridor created for these huge powerlines.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/12-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/12-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Pinwheels Vista, a breathtaking view of the surrounding flatlands of New Jersey. No shower in sight.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/13-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/13-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Out of New Jersey and into New York! State #9!\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/13b-768x1024.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/13b-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Taking a break from all the grueling hiking for a nice float in Upper Goose Pond, Massachusetts\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/14-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/14-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Pair of shoes #4 and #5, Bennington, Vermont\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/15-1024x820.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/15-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Firetower atop Glastenbury Mountain, Vermont. One of my favorite places on the trail.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/16-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/16-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"View from Glastenbury firetower, Vermont\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/17-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/17-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Our coffee drinking habits are slightly more time consuming in the woods.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/18-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/18-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Little Rock Pond, Vermont. Crystal clear waters like this one were abounding along the Appalachian Trail in New England.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/19-768x1024.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/19-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"View from atop Baker Peak in Vermont for a magnificent sunset as the enormous, confident mountains stand motionless surrounding Baker\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/20-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/20-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"White Rock Cliffs in Vermont. The wind blows strong overlooking this silent wilderness without a single sign of human life anywhere.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/21-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/21-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The man with the sharpie speaks only truth. Upon a fork in the path, if you\'re not sure which follows the AT, follow the path that goes straight up.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/22-1024x767.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/22-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\'A fellow thru-hiker posts encouragement upon a tree: \"You&apos;ve officially hiked as far as Frodo did in Lord of the Rings&mdash;1800 miles.\"\' href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/23-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/23-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Standing on the top of Mount Moosilauke in New Hampshire&mdash;the first mountain in the White Mountains with the most intimidating elevation profile so far.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/24-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/24-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Clouds rolling over the top of Mount Kinsman, New Hampshire after days of rain. This was one of the hardest climbs on the Appalachian Trail.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/25-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/25-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The serene Kinsman Pond on Mount Kinsman.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/26-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/26-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A leisurely breakfast on top of Mount Liberty, New Hampshire. The White Mountains are famous for their unbelievable views and dramatic ups and downs.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/27-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/27-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"On top of Mount Lafayette in the middle of the famous Franconia Ridge. Luckily the 4 months of hiking have left me in better condition than whatever happened to the guy passed out on the rock in the background.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/28-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/28-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Mount Garfield, New Hampshire. In the background, you can see the virgin wilderness of the Pemigewassett Wilderness with Owl\'s Head Mountain directly in the center.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/29-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/29-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"View back to Mount Lafayette from Mount Garfield\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/30-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/30-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Mount Washington in the White Mountains of New Hampshire&mdash;second highest elevation on the Appalachian Trail.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/31-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/31-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A fellow hiker, Sourpatch, hikes onward across the Presidential Mountain Range in New Hampshire&mdash;one of the most intense yet unbelievable ranges on the entire trail. Although the photographs cannot capture it, these mountains are so big that you cannot comprehend.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/32-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/32-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Hiking down the backside of Mount Adams. With a 1,500 foot drop in less than a mile, Mount Adams was the baddest of the bad in the Presidentials.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/33-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/33-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Getting some relax time in overlooking Carter Notch after descending Wildcat Mountain (pictured) and beginning the climb up Carter Dome.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/34-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/34-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Guess who made it to Maine! 1900 miles down and 280 to go!\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/35-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/35-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Standing on top of Goose Eye Mountain, one of Maine\'s most beautiful mountains. The territory has changed from the popular hiking areas of the White Mountains to the vast uninhabited wilderness of Maine.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/36-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/36-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Mahoosuc Notch, the most technically difficult mile to hike on the AT. The notch is a ravine of jumbled, truck-sized fallen boulders with cliffs going straight up on either side.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/37-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/37-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"For someone who has lived within society for their entire life, the vast emptiness of Maine is almost incomprehensible.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/38-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/38-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Baldpate Mountain, Maine&mdash;a rocky, treeless summit allows you to see all around you.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/39-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/39-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A view from the summit of Baldpate.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/40-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/40-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"2000 miles down! Only 189 miles left.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/41-1024x707.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/41-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The final 100 miles of the AT are known as the 100 Mile Wilderness and have no places to travel into town for supplies...or for anything else.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/42-1024x663.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/42-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"My first view of Katahdin three days before my summit was even more climactic than I imagined.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/43-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/43-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The pack that I carried for 6 months, over 2000 miles from Georgia to Maine. If you want a quality pack, get an Osprey.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/44-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/44-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Man is born to die. His works are short lived. Buildings crumble, monuments decay, wealth vanishes but Katahdin in all its glory forever shall remain the mountain of the people of Maine.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/45-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/45-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The view from within the clouds on top of Mount Katahdin, the northern terminus of the Appalachian Trail.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/46-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/46-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"After 6 months of hiking 15-25 miles every single day with little rest, I stand on top of the marker of the northern terminus of the Appalachian Trail on Mount Katahdin, Maine, October 15th, 2015.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/47-641x1024.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/47-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The view of Knife Edge from Baxter Peak, Katahdin&mdash;a trail that travels on the very pointed ridgeline and down the north side of Katahdin.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/48-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/48-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The Knife Edge\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/49-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/49-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The Knife Edge\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/50-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/50-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The Knife Edge travels along the pointed ridgeline with dramatic dropoffs on either side.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/51-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/51-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The Knife Edge travels along the pointed ridgeline with dramatic dropoffs on either side.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/52-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/52-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"A view from along Knife Edge back to Baxter Peak, the summit of Katahdin.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/53-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/53-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Knife Edge\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/55-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/55-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"The incredible view of the orange autumn colors from the top of Katahdin, Maine\'s greatest mountain.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/56-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/56-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\'The most dramatic part of the Knife Edge, straight down and back up&mdash;\"The Saddle\".\' href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/57-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/57-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Twigs and Die Free show their excitement down in The Saddle.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/58-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/58-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"Three successful thru-hikers pose together after their completion of the amazing Knife Edge.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/59-1024x768.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/59-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"photo-thumb\">\n		<a title=\"disconnect, aka Russell Strauss, 2015 Appalachian Trail thru-hiker.\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/60-1024x773.jpg\" rel=\"shadowbox[AT]\">\n			<img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/60-150x150.jpg\">\n		</a>\n	</div>\n	<div class=\"clearfix\"></div>\n</div>\n ','2189 miles','','inherit','open','open','','699-autosave-v1','','','2018-06-13 18:27:30','2018-06-13 18:27:30','',699,'http://portfolio.dev/699-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(768,1,'2016-04-07 14:49:55','2016-04-07 14:49:55','In April of 2015, I left my home in Atlanta with two of my friends to drive up to Springer Mountain in north Georgia. We planned a 4-day backpacking trip from the peak of Springer, the southern terminus of the famous Appalachian Trail, to Neels Gap, 32 miles northeast. While Winston and Ryan, the two friends that had joined me for the weekend and Winston\'s dog, Orion, planned only to travel to Neels Gap before returning home to Atlanta, I had committed to something very different. I had spent the last year planning the logistics and mentally preparing to hike the entire length of the Appalachian Trail from start to finish within a single calendar year. \r\n\r\nYou can look anywhere for information on thru-hiking (hiking the length of a trail in a single trip) and find all sorts of statistics that will discourage you from attempting a thru-hike of the AT: \"Only 1 in 5 people who set out to thru-hike make it to the end of the trail\"; \"The elevation change in thru-hiking the AT is equivalent to climbing up and down Mount Everest 16 times\"; \"Many hikers give up within the first week and many others 1-2 months into the trip when the monotony of hiking for 8+ hours a day becomes no longer enjoyable\"; \"The Appalachian Trail is the wettest long distance hiking trail in the U.S.\"; and plenty of other anecdotes from hikers discussing the hardships of long distance hiking. \r\n\r\nBut one of the most crucial facts that must not be forgotten is that despite all of the hardships that come with the nature of long distance hiking, many very strong benefits accompany the lifestyle of a backpacker as well&mdash;a life without traffic, bills to pay, the bureaucratic frustrations of civilized life; a life without appointments or schedules to follow. \r\n\r\nOf course, though there are no schedules to follow, there is one schedule that relentlessly demands progress: walk. And that \"walk\" is certainly almost nothing like what you might casually visualize as a constant but leisurely stroll forward. It is a walk through mud pits, over boulders, up and down constant changes in elevation. It is waking up and walking as quickly as you can until it\'s time to sleep. It is having to walk all day in the rain when you already got sick of rain days ago. It is a walk full of tumbles and falls up and down huge slanted slabs of slippery wet rock.\r\n\r\nBut when you\'re not falling, when you\'re not walking in the rain, when you\'re not uncomfortable, hungry, or exhausted from carrying thirty pounds on your back, the sun shines brightly upon your face. You\'re soaked in sweat, but you\'re in charge of nothing but your own well-being. You have an infinite amount of freedom...as long as you never stop walking. You physically struggle during the day, but find comfort in the incredible luxury of a packet of ramen noodles in the evening. So I wasn\'t going home until I had hiked the entire Appalachian Trail. I wasn\'t worried about the statistics. I had what I needed, and all I had to do was keep moving.\r\n\r\nI walked from Georgia to Maine. I started in April and finished in October. I owned only what was light enough to carry on my back day after day across mountaintops for 2,200 miles. Even in these conditions, I often carried more than I really needed. The lifestyle of a backpacker is simple and serene. It is also rigorous and full of hardship.  If you ever get the opportunity to live with only what you can carry on your back, <em>I suggest you take it.</em>','2189 miles using featherlight','','draft','closed','closed','','2189-miles-post','','','2016-04-08 14:20:52','2016-04-08 14:20:52','',0,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/?p=768',-500,'post','',0),(765,1,'2015-11-12 22:20:20','2015-11-12 22:20:20','<div class=\"section\">\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> <div class=\"small-12 columns\"> <h1>Contact</h1> </div> </div>\r\n					\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> \r\n		<div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns item\"><span class=\"plus\">+ </span>Phone </div> <div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns\"> 678.927.3289 </div>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> \r\n		<div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns item\"><span class=\"plus\">+ </span>Email </div> <div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns\"> <a href=\"mailto:russellstrauss@gmail.com\">russellstrauss@gmail.com</a> </div>\r\n	</div>\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> \r\n		<div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns item\"><span class=\"plus\">+ </span>Portfolio </div> <div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns\"> <a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/work/\">http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/work/</a> </div>\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n				\r\n\r\n<div class=\"section\">\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> <div class=\"small-12 columns\"> <h1>Education</h1> </div> </div>\r\n					\r\n	<div class=\"row undergraduate\"> \r\n		<div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns subhead\"><span class=\"plus\">+ </span>Undergraduate </div>\r\n					\r\n		<div class=\"large-6 small-12 columns listed-item\">\r\n			<ul>\r\n				<li>Georgia Institute of Technology</li>\r\n				<li>B.S. Computational Media \'12</li>\r\n				<li>Magna Cum Laude</li>\r\n				<li>GPA 3.5</li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n				\r\n<div class=\"section\">\r\n	<div class=\"row\"> <div class=\"small-12 columns\"> <h1>Skills</h1> </div> </div>\r\n					\