our own well-being. You have an infinite amount of freedom...as long as you never stop walking. You physically struggle during the day, but find comfort in the incredible luxury of a packet of ramen noodles in the evening. So I wasn\'t going home until I had hiked the entire Appalachian Trail. I wasn\'t worried about the statistics. I had what I needed, and all I had to do was keep moving.\r\n\r\nI walked from Georgia to Maine. I started in April and finished in October. I owned only what was light enough to carry on my back day after day across mountaintops for 2,200 miles. Even in these conditions, I often carried more than I really needed. The lifestyle of a backpacker is simple and serene. It is also rigorous and full of hardship.  If you ever get the opportunity to live with only what you can carry on your back, <em>I suggest you take it.</em>','2189 miles using featherlight','','inherit','open','open','','768-revision-v1','','','2016-04-08 14:20:38','2016-04-08 14:20:38','',768,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/768-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(778,1,'2017-04-27 03:12:05','2017-04-27 03:12:05','A web site is a powerful tool. It allows companies to divert resources from customer services, users to reference information freely at their own leisure, brands to direct attention to their social media channels, retailers to offer services that they previously could not, and organizations to spread information more effectively than they ever could without a web presence. There are certainly hundreds of other advantages to invest in web services and mobile applications than I could ever even take the time to list out, but the reasoning is all the same: having a web site is not just an option for a successful business in the 21st century&mdash;it is crucial.','Web Development','','inherit','open','open','','64-revision-v1','','','2017-04-27 03:12:05','2017-04-27 03:12:05','',64,'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/64-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(782,1,'2018-04-10 03:3